Spring AOP:
  Spring AOP allows you to separate cross-cutting concerns (logic used across multiple places) from business logic.
  Instead of repeating code → write once, apply everywhere.
Cross-cutting concerns:
    Logging
    Security
    Transactions
    Caching
    Auditing

Core Concepts:
🔹 1. Aspect- A class containing cross-cutting logic.
      @Aspect
      @Component
      public class LoggingAspect {
      }
🔹 2. Advice (When to execute)
      Type	            Description
      @Before	          Before method
      @After	          After method
      @AfterReturning	  After success
      @AfterThrowing	  On exception
      @Around	          Full control
🔹 3. Pointcut (Where to apply)
        @Pointcut("execution(* com.app.service.*.*(..))")
        public void serviceLayer() {}
       Means: apply to all methods in service package
        Types of Pointcut Expressions:
            🔹 1. execution() - execution(* com.app.service.*.*(..)) -> Most commonly used
            🔹 2. within() - within(com.app.service..*) -> Targets class/package
            🔹 3. args() - args(String, int) -> Based on method arguments
            🔹 4. @annotation() -  @annotation(org.springframework.transaction.annotation.Transactional) -> Apply AOP to annotated methods   
            🔹 5. this() vs target():
                  this(com.app.MyInterface). this → proxy type
                  target(com.app.MyClass).target → actual object
🔹 4. Join Point
        A specific method execution point
        Any point in program execution where an aspect can be applied
        In full AOP (like AspectJ), join points include:
              Method execution ✅
              Method call
              Constructor execution
              Field access (get/set)
              Exception handling
         In Spring AOP:
              ✅ ONLY method execution is supported as a Join Point
              ❌ NOT supported:
                    Field access
                    Constructor join points
                    Static blocks
                 Because Spring AOP is proxy-based, not bytecode weaving.
             JoinPoint Object (Runtime Info)- 
        You can access details of the method being executed:
              @Before("execution(* com.app.service.*.*(..))")
              public void log(JoinPoint jp) {
                  System.out.println(jp.getSignature().getName());
                  System.out.println(Arrays.toString(jp.getArgs()));
              }
        What you can get from JoinPoint:
                Method	            Description
                getSignature()	    Method name
                getArgs()	          Arguments
                getTarget()	        Actual object
                getThis()	          Proxy object
        Types Related to Join Points:
            🔹 1. JoinPoint:
                  Used in all advice types
                  Read-only (cannot control execution)
            🔹 2. ProceedingJoinPoint (Special)
                   Used only in @Around
                    @Around("execution(* *(..))")
                    public Object around(ProceedingJoinPoint pjp) throws Throwable {
                        return pjp.proceed(); // controls execution
                    }
         Extra Powers:
              Skip method execution
              Modify arguments
              Change return value
      Join Point vs Pointcut:
        Feature	      Join Point	            Pointcut
        Meaning	      Actual execution point	Expression to select join points
        Example	      Method call	            execution(* service.*(..))
        Runtime	      Yes	                    No (just matcher)
     Simple:
          Join Point = real place
          Pointcut = filter
🔹 5. Proxy 
        Spring AOP works using proxy pattern
         This is the heart of AOP

Internal Working (Step-by-Step):
    @Service
    public class PaymentService {
        public void pay() {
            System.out.println("Payment done");
        }
    }
What Spring Does Internally
    Step 1: Bean Creation - Spring creates PaymentService bean
    Step 2: Check for Aspects - Spring finds @Aspect classes
    Step 3: Create Proxy Object - Instead of original object, Spring creates: 👉 Proxy(PaymentService)
                              Two types:
                                  JDK Dynamic Proxy → if interface exists
                                  CGLIB → if no interface
    Step 4: Method Call Flow
          Client → Proxy → Aspect → Target Method → Aspect → Return
 Flow Diagram:
    User call
       ↓
    Proxy Object
       ↓
    @Before Advice
       ↓
    Actual Method
       ↓
    @After Advice
       ↓
    Return
    
Complete Example
🔹 Service Class
      @Service
      public class UserService {
          public String getUser() {
              return "User data";
          }
      }
🔹 Aspect Class
        @Aspect
        @Component
        public class LoggingAspect {
            @Before("execution(* com.app.service.*.*(..))")
            public void beforeMethod(JoinPoint jp) {
                System.out.println("Before: " + jp.getSignature().getName());
            }
            @AfterReturning(
                pointcut = "execution(* com.app.service.*.*(..))",
                returning = "result")
            public void afterMethod(Object result) {
                System.out.println("Returned: " + result);
            }
        }
🔹 Output
    Before: getUser
    Returned: User data
    
 @Around Advice:
      @Around("execution(* com.app.service.*.*(..))")
      public Object around(ProceedingJoinPoint pjp) throws Throwable {
          System.out.println("Before execution");
          Object result = pjp.proceed(); // actual method call
          System.out.println("After execution");
          return result;
      }
 You can:
    Modify input
    Skip method
    Change output
    
🚀 Real-Time Usage
🔹 1. Logging
        @Before("execution(* *(..))")
        public void log() {}
🔹 2. Transactions
     Behind the scenes:  @Transactional  Uses AOP to: Start transaction and Commit / rollback
🔹 3. Security
      @PreAuthorize("hasRole('ADMIN')")  Uses AOP to check permissions
🔹 4. Performance Monitoring
        @Around
        // measure execution time
🔹 5. Caching
      @Cacheable
     AOP checks cache before calling method

 Important Limitations:
❌ 1. Works only on Spring Beans - Not on new objects
❌ 2. Self-invocation problem - this.method2(); // AOP won't work 👉 Because proxy is bypassed  
❌ 3. Only public methods - Private/Final methods not intercepted
❌ 4. Runtime only - Not compile-time like AspectJ

 Advanced Concepts:
🔹 Multiple Aspects Order
      @Order(1)
      @Aspect
      class A {}  
      @Order(2)
      @Aspect
      class B {}
    Lower number = higher priority
🔹 Pointcut Expressions
      execution(public * com.app.service.UserService.get*(..))
      👉 Breakdown:
          public → access modifier
          → return type
          get* → method name pattern
          (..) → any arguments
          
 AOP vs Filter vs Interceptor
Feature	      AOP	            Filter  	        Interceptor
Level	        Method	        Servlet	          Spring MVC
Use case	    Business logic	Request/Response	Controller
Example	      @Transactional	Authentication	  Logging


1: Difference between JoinPoint and ProceedingJoinPoint?
      JoinPoint      	ProceedingJoinPoint
      Read-only	      Can control execution
      All advice	    Only @Around
2: Why Spring AOP supports only method execution?
      Because:
      It uses proxy pattern
      Not bytecode weaving (like AspectJ)
3: Can we modify method arguments?-> ✅ Only with ProceedingJoinPoint ; pjp.proceed(newArgs);
4: Does AOP work on static methods? 👉 ❌ No
5: What happens if multiple aspects match same join point? 👉 All will execute based on @Order
6: What is weaving?
    Process of applying aspects:
        Compile-time (AspectJ)
        Load-time
        Runtime (Spring AOP)
